      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d51fb2c98c0ac480",
      "text": "However, if you now thought that letting yourself be found by a solution was a purely passive attitude, then perhaps this was often the reason why it was difficult to let yourself be found by a solution."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "50827ba5a08c0a2c",
      "text": "To let oneself be found by a solution requires a lot of commitment – but a commitment of attitudes from which the actions follow and not vice versa."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "008785e95bff8d87",
      "text": "If we are looking for this changed attitude towards attitudes and actions of change, the [[Tetralemma]] can help us to let such attitudes find us."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98ae544cc836820a",
      "text": "An indispensable prerequisite for being found by solutions is the assumption that the solution and all the resources required for it really exist. We began to practice this change of attitude earlier in the text with the wonder question. A lateral thinker puts himself in the position of someone who has already found, and asks himself:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a02fc0d4ba5826d4",
      "text": "If overnight, miraculously, I had already found what I was about – what would be different? What would I do then that I am not doing now?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dbd4f7d3aee1f953",
      "text": "The lateral thinker has visualized the miracle through this leap into a possible future, viewing it as something past rather than something future (a procedure Erickson has called and explored as pseudoprojection in time; see, among others, Erickson 1998, pp. 178-181)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "2d07e5043bb9653a",
      "text": "If you consider the consequences of the solution by the miracle question, problems can often disappear in the traceless way we have explained with Wittgenstein's examples; because thereby the problem aspects are dissolved, which existed only in an obstructive arrangement of the parts."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fea1587ac4a36e0b",
      "text": "For the rearrangement of the parts, the grammar of the word \"problem\" and the consideration of possible arrangements of focus, goal, obstacles, resources, profit and future task gives us important cross-thinking impulses, which we have introduced in the idea of the problem constellation."
    },
